I personally do not believe communion saves a person (that is by faith in Jesus Christ), but that communion is a sacrament, a way in which we receive God's grace, which is distinguishable from regenerating grace.  As a side note, and NOT to offend my fellow mates here, but I believe that one of the abuses of commemorating the Lord's Supper is to be found by a look at Roman/world history.  The threat of excommunication, as an ecclesiastical sentence, was/is taken very seriously, as if man has the ability to withold God's grace from the body of believers.<br>
<br>
With your questions about WHO may be blessed, or 'anointed' to offer communion, (I've thought about this too), think also of the sacrament of marriage....are we married then because the priest has said words over us?  or is the true marriage when two people enter into a covenant with God?<br>
<br>
I have much to do in studying about this, but I think maybe some of your/our concerns rest on our ability to look at the 'gifts' of the church (the Body-of Christ--all believers)  Paul writes much about the specific gifts and qualification of the 'leaders' of the church. (I'll try to put my finger on specific verses later this morning), certainly, even in Christ's days on earth, marriage was a sacrament, and a priest joined together two in a ceremony.....<br>
<br>
And, regarding taking communion in an unworthy manner...take a look at 1 Cor. 11:23-33.  Paul says that vs.26)for as often as you eat this bread and drink the cup, you proclaim the Lord's death until He comes...therefore whoever eats the bread or drinks the cup of the Lord in an unworthy manner, shall be guilty of the body and the blood of the Lord.  But a man must examine himself, and in so doing he is to eat of the bread and drink of the cup.  <br>
