<br>
Moderator hat here for a moment.<br>
<br>
I also don't think that Jeff intended an overt or even veiled questioning of another Christian's salvation.  It's one of the biggest no no's here and I know that neither HJ or I would let that happen.<br>
<br>
I could honestly post something very similar from Roman Catholic doctrine, as in that regard both it and Orthodoxy are quite similar.  However, there is a caveat in the Roman Catholic doctrine under their ecumenical writings which do say that there is much of God and the Holy Spirit with our &quot;separated brethren&quot; and that God's grace can and does act in a regenerative manner with those people.  While it would likely condemn the person who originally came up with what they consider false doctrine, they do not condemn those who follow such doctrine, provided it remains - for the most part - within orthodox Christian belief.<br>
<br>
I don't know if the Orthodox chruch also carries this caveat, but I would think it would be likely.  So while they may believe that Christians within their church are saved in that manner, it is not necessarily the way that all Christians are saved.<br>
<br>
I hope that makes things sound a little better, for all concerned.  I now return you to your regular thread. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p>Christians know that it is not possible to reject or ignore God without demeaning man<br>
- John Paul II at WYD 2002<br>
<br>
